                "transcript":"<p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-size: 110%; font-weight: bold\">Asset Liquidity</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[Start with these words on the screen on the left: Short-term assets/Converted to Cash or Consumed < 1 year]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Short-term assets. Converted to Cash or Consumed within 1 year. </p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[A business person holding fanned out bills.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">The most liquid asset is cash. Cash does not even need to be converted into cash. Cash is already cash!</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[Person holding the person holding cash fades out. Fade in a person holding a certificate or piece of paper at an exchange counter. They give the paper to a person behind the counter, who gives them cash.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Some other assets are so liquid—that is, so easy to convert into cash—that they are called “cash equivalents.” An example of a cash equivalent is a short-term government bond like a Treasury Bill. They are extremely easy to convert into cash for their full value.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Long-term assets. Held > 1 year.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Examples: Equipment and real estate. </p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Have you ever tried to sell an office building?</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[Two business people, one standing by an office building.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Man: Hey, do you want to buy our building for $50 million?</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[A bag of money labeled “$50 million” appears near the the building.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Woman: Maybe. Let me check with my colleagues.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[Woman leaves. First stays on screen. Monthly calendar pages are torn off—January, February, March. Woman comes back.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Woman: OK, maybe. But we’ll need to get a valuation done.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Man: But wait. We need to sell this right now.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Woman: Well that would be a big risk for us. You’d have to give us a discount. How about $30 million?</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[$50 million changes to $30 million]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Illiquid assets are difficult to convert to cash quickly. Or, if they must be converted to cash quickly, the seller may have to accept less in payment than it otherwise might receive.</p>"
