				"module": "1",
                "thumb_image": "2.4.png",
				"label": "2.4: Normal Debit Balances and Normal Credit Balances",
                "video_url": "https://ry6g4c.cloud.influxis.com/ManagedContent/361_Video2-4_h264_baseline_l31_3500k_720p_aac_96k.mp4",
                "transcript": "<p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-size: 110%; font-weight: bold\">Normal Debit and Credit Balances</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-weight:bold;\">Accounts with normal debit balance:</p><ul><li>Debits increase the account balance</li><li>When debits are greater than credits, the account balance is positive (> 0)</li><li>At the end of the accounting period, debits normally exceed credits</li></ul><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-weight:bold;\">Accounts with normal credit balance:</p><ul><li>Credits increase the account balance</li><li>When credits are greater than debits, the account balance is positive (> 0)</li><li>At the end of the accounting period, credits normally exceed debits</li></ul><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-weight:bold;\">Accounts with normal debit balance:</p><ul><li>Asset accounts</li><li>Expense accounts</li></ul><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-weight:bold;\">Accounts with normal credit balance:</p><ul><li>Liability accounts</li><li>Revenue accounts</li><li>Owners’ equity accounts</li></ul><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[Man walks on screen]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">You might be thinking, “How am I supposed to remember that!?” One way is to memorize it.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Here’s another way. Remember the basic accounting equation?</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[Screen is wiped blank.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-weight:bold;\">Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Revenues usually increase Assets, while expenses usually reduce them. So, we can expand the equation like this:</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-weight:bold;\">Assets = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity + Revenues - Expenses</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">If you add Expenses to both sides of the equation, you get:</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-weight:bold;\">Assets + Expenses = Liabilities + Owners’ Equity + Revenues</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[An arrow pointing to the left side of the equation.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Assets and Expenses are on the left side. </p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[An arrow pointing to the right side of the equation.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Liabilities, Owners’ Equity, and Revenues are on the right side.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[Arrows pointing to both sides of the equation.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Debits are associated with the left, and credits with the right.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[Label under the left arrow, “Normal Debit Balance,” appears.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Therefore, asset accounts and expense accounts have a normal debit balance.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[Label under the right arrow, “Normal Credit Balance,” appears.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">And liability, owners’ equity, and revenue accounts all have a normal credit balance.</p>"
