                "transcript": "<p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-size: 110%; font-weight: bold\">The Realization Principle and the Matching Principle</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">The Gunnison Life Insurance Company issues a group disability insurance policy to the Coney Hill Company.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[A timeline appears with markers for January 1, March 31, June 30, September 30, and December 31.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">The policy will provide coverage to Coney Hill’s employees from January 1 through December 31. The annual premium for this policy is $40,000. The premium is payable in quarterly installments of $10,000.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[An arrow appears below the timeline marker for January 1, labeled “$10,000”. An arrow appears below the timeline marker for March 31, labeled “$10,000, April 1.” An arrow appears below the timeline marker for June 30, labeled “$10,000, July 1.” An arrow appears below the timeline marker for September 30, labeled “$10,000, October 1.” The arrows fade out.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">However, Coney Hill decides to prepay the entire $40,000 annual premium on January 1. How will Gunnison recognize this annual premium?</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[An arrow appears below the timeline marker for January 1, labeled “$40,000.”]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">In accordance with the realization principle, it recognizes revenue when it is earned.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[The arrow below January 1 fades out.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">So even though Gunnison received $40,000 at the start of the first quarter…</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[“$40,000 received” appears above the January 1 marker.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">… it earned only $10,000 during the first quarter.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[“$10,000 earned” appears below “$40,000 received.” They both fade out.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">It recognizes $10,000 on its first quarterly income statement.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[“Income Statement, $10,000” appears above the March 31 marker.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">It earned $10,000 more in each of the second, third, and fourth quarters and so recognizes $10,000 on each quarterly income statement.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[“Income Statement, $10,000” appears above the June 30 marker while an arrow appears below. Then both fade out. “Income Statement, $10,000” appears above the September 30 marker while an arrow appears below. Then both fade out. “Income Statement, $10,000” appears above the December 31 marker while an arrow appears below. Then both fade out.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Suppose Gunnison incurred $6,800 of expenses for Coney Hill’s insurance coverage during the first quarter. How will the insurer recognize this expense?</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[“Expenses, $6,800” appears between January 1 and March 31 on the timeline.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">According to the matching principle, the company recognizes expenses as it earns the revenues related to those expenses.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[“Expenses, $6,800” fades out.]</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">So Gunnison recognizes the first quarter expenses on the first quarter income statement.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">[An arrow appears under the March 31 marker, while “Expenses, $6,800” appears above.]</p>"
