                "transcript": "<p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-size:110%;\"><strong>Bond Discounts and Premiums</strong></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>Show the bond certificate image from Figure 5.4 and the first line of text above the bond </em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Remember our bond?</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[A bond certificate appears with a par value of $1,000, a coupon rate of 5%, and a maturity date of July 15, 2030.]</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Question: how often does a bond sell for its par value?</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[Arrow points at $1,000 on the bond.]</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Answer: almost never!</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Why? Because market interest rates change all the time and are almost never the same as the bond&rsquo;s coupon rate.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[Arrow points at 5% on the bond.]</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Market interest rates are the rates that investors can get on bonds and other investments in the investment markets.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[Two bar graphs, one for Market Interest Rate with a line at the top marked &ldquo;Coupon Rate&rdquo; and one for Bond Price with a line at the top marked &ldquo;Par Value.&rdquo;</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">An existing bond&rsquo;s price generally changes in a direction that is inversely related to changes in market interest rates. That is, if market interest rates rise, then the prices of existing bonds fall.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[The Market Interest Rate graph grows above the &ldquo;Coupon Rate&rdquo; line and the Bond Price graph shrinks below the &ldquo;Par Value&rdquo; line.]</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">If market interest rates are <u>higher</u> than the bond&rsquo;s coupon rate, the bond will sell for les<u>s</u> than the par value. This is known as &ldquo;selling at a <strong>discount</strong>.&rdquo;</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[A bracket labeled &ldquo;Discount&rdquo; appears next to the gap between the top of the Bond Price graph and the &ldquo;Par Value&rdquo; line.]</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">If market interest rates fall, then the price of existing bonds rise.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[The Market Interest Rate graph shrinks below the &ldquo;Coupon Rate&rdquo; line and the Bond Price graph grows above the &ldquo;Par Value&rdquo; line.]</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">If market interest rates are <u>lower</u> than the bond&rsquo;s coupon rate, the bond will sell for more than the par value. This is known as &ldquo;selling at a <strong>premium</strong>.&rdquo;</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[A bracket labeled &ldquo;Premiumn&rdquo; appears next to the extra graph between the top of the Bond Price graph and the &ldquo;Par Value&rdquo; line.]</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[A bond certificate appears with a par value of $1,000, a coupon rate of 5%, and a maturity date of July 15, 2030.]</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">The interest paid is always the par value multiplied by the coupon rate.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[Arrows point at $1,000 and 5% on the bond.]</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">None of these affect the amount of interest the bond issuer pays:</p><ul><li><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Market interest rate</p></li><li><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Current bond value</p></li><li><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Current owner&rsquo;s purchase price</p></li></ul><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">This particular bond will pay 5% until it matures, no matter what happens with market interest rates.</p>"
