				"module": "2",
                "thumb_image": "7.1.png",
				"label": "7.1: Relationship between Reserves and Surplus",
				"video_url": "http://ry6g4c.cloud.influxis.com/ManagedContent/361_Video7-1_h264_baseline_l31_3500k_720p_aac_96k.mp4",
                "transcript": "<p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left; font-size:110%;\"><strong>Relationship between Reserves and Surplus</strong></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>Assets = Liabilities + Owners&rsquo; Equity</em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">Reserves are liabilities.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\"><em>[Arrow points at &ldquo;Liabilities&rdquo; in the equation.] </em></p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">In fact, reserves make up by far the majority of an insurer&rsquo;s liabilities.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">If an insurer underestimates its reserves, it overstates its surplus. This must be true, because otherwise the accounting equation would be out of balance.</p><p style=\"width: 100%; text-align:left;\">If the insurer overestimates its reserves, it overstates its surplus.</p>"
